{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"## Why\nConfig PERSISTENCE + reconciler-READ are already solved: `resolve_jira_settings` (`src/rebar/_engine/rebar_reconciler/acli_subprocess.py`) resolves url/user/project through `load_config().jira.*` (typed `JiraConfig`, reading `rebar.toml [jira]` / `pyproject.toml [tool.rebar.jira]` / legacy `.rebar/config.conf`), env overriding, token env-only; `rebar bridge-probe` validates credentials end-to-end. The ONLY missing piece is an INTERACTIVE onboarding UX.\n\n## What\nAdd an interactive `rebar jira-onboard` subcommand (intercept, like `rebar llm`/`reconcile`; owns its own `--help`) that detects existing Jira settings via `resolve_jira_settings`, prompts for missing url/user/project, persists them to the typed config, guides on the env-only token, and runs `bridge-probe` validation. Mirror the `rebar llm setup` precedent. New impl: `src/rebar/_cli/_jira_onboard.py`.\n\n## Scope\n- New `rebar jira-onboard` CLI intercept (Python). Detect via `resolve_jira_settings()`. Prompt for missing url/user/project. Flags: `--url/--user/--project` (non-interactive), `--no-validate`, `--reset` (clears persisted jira keys), `--yes` (skip --reset confirmation).\n- Persist via a NEW writer `write_jira_config(...)` in `src/rebar/config.py`. Token NEVER written.\n- Reuse `bridge-probe` as the post-onboard check.\n- Out: any new config read LAYER, persisting secrets, editing a user's pyproject.toml, touching the reconciler read path.\n\n## Mechanism â€” config write (resolves the section-boundary BLOCK; G6/T1/T2/T3/T9/E1)\n- Add `write_jira_config(url, user, project, *, root=None, clear=False) -> Path | None` to `config.py`. Atomic (write tmp file in the same dir + `os.replace`).\n- **Dependency choice â€” justified (T1).** rebar's engine is deliberately stdlib-only (`dependencies = []`; core has only pyyaml/jsonschema/referencing). Adding `tomlkit`/`tomli-w` would regress that for one onboarding writer. Captured durably as an ADR (see Files: `docs/adr/0001-jira-onboard-config-write.md`).\n- **No line-scanning / no surgical splice (kills the section-boundary + inline-table + dotted-key hazards entirely, T2/G6).** The writer NEVER does text-region splicing. Instead it is a full parse -> mutate -> re-emit of a REBAR-OWNED file only:\n  1. Resolve the write target (rule below) -> always a rebar-owned `rebar.toml` (or legacy conf), NEVER a user `pyproject.toml`.\n  2. If the target `rebar.toml` exists, READ it whole with stdlib `tomllib` into a dict (this correctly understands every valid TOML form â€” `[jira]` section, `jira = {inline}`, `jira.url` dotted â€” they all parse to the same nested dict, so there is no form-specific code and no way to append a duplicate section). A `tomllib.TOMLDecodeError` -> clear error, NO write.\n  3. Mutate the in-memory dict: set/replace `jira.url/user/project` (or delete those three keys when `clear=True`; if the `jira` table becomes empty, drop it).\n  4. Re-EMIT the entire dict with a small, self-contained, fully-specified TOML serializer (`_emit_toml(dict)` â€” emits top-level scalars, then `[section]` tables with `key = \"value\"` lines; only the value types rebar config uses: str/bool/int/list-of-str). Deterministic key order. Because we re-serialize the whole rebar-owned file, there is NO section-end-boundary problem â€” boundaries are produced by the emitter, not detected. Comment loss is acceptable on a rebar-owned config file (we never re-emit a user pyproject).\n- **Write-target rule (deterministic, E2).** Use `_discover_project_config(root)`:\n  - returns a `toml` (`rebar.toml`) -> that file is the target (read-mutate-emit).\n  - returns a `pyproject` or `legacy`, OR returns None -> the target is `<repo_root>/rebar.toml`. For `pyproject`/None we CREATE rebar.toml (it wins read precedence per the discovery walk: rebar.toml is probed before pyproject). For `legacy`, we ALSO write `rebar.toml` (the typed loader reads it; the legacy file is left untouched) â€” simpler and avoids a second format path. (The legacy READ path stays supported by load_config; we just persist forward to rebar.toml.)\n  - Net: there is exactly ONE write format (`rebar.toml` via the emitter). No second hand-rolled format. `--reset` is the same path with `clear=True`.\n\n## Mechanism â€” validation env bridge (resolves prior BLOCK; T3)\n- `bridge-probe` (`jira-capability-probe.py`) reads `JIRA_URL/USER/PROJECT/API_TOKEN` from `os.environ`. `_bridge_probe()` currently hardcodes `env=engine_env()`. FIX: `_bridge_probe(argv, *, extra_env=None)` merges an optional overlay onto `engine_env()`. The wizard re-resolves via `resolve_jira_settings()` and passes resolved url/user/project as `extra_env` so the probe sees what was persisted.\n\n## Failure / edge paths + decisions (T4/T6/COH/F1)\n- Empty input at a required prompt re-prompts; EOF/Ctrl-C aborts cleanly (exit 1, NO write â€” all input is collected BEFORE any write). Config-write `OSError` -> reported, non-zero. Existing rebar.toml with a TOML syntax error -> caught `TOMLDecodeError` -> clear error, no write.\n- **Probe behavior (AC explicit): with JIRA_API_TOKEN set -> run bridge-probe (resolved settings injected); token ABSENT or `--no-validate` -> probe is SKIPPED, a guidance message is printed, exit 0.** A failing probe (token present, Jira rejects) surfaces PROBE_FAIL and returns the probe's non-zero code; the persisted config is KEPT.\n- **`--reset` flow (explicit):** clears the three jira keys then EXITS (no inline re-prompt). Confirms first unless `--yes`; declining -> exit 1, no change. To reconfigure, run `rebar jira-onboard` again.\n- **rebar.toml-creation rollback (explicit):** when the wizard creates a new rebar.toml on a pyproject-configured repo, the completion message + help text state: \"Created rebar.toml at <path>; to revert to pyproject.toml config, delete rebar.toml.\"\n- TOCTOU: single-operator interactive tool; concurrent runs out of scope. `os.replace` guarantees no torn file; the read-modify-write last-writer-wins window is documented in the writer docstring.\n- Docs (T7): `docs/jira-sync-setup.md` gets a `rebar jira-onboard` section AND its existing manual TOML-edit / token steps are reconciled to cross-reference the wizard as the recommended path (not left to contradict it).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `rebar jira-onboard` detects existing settings via `resolve_jira_settings` and prompts only for missing url/user/project.\n- [ ] On confirm it persists url/user/project to a rebar-owned `rebar.toml` `[jira]` section via `write_jira_config` (parse-mutate-emit; never edits a user pyproject.toml; never line-splices).\n- [ ] With JIRA_API_TOKEN set it runs `bridge-probe` with resolved settings injected into the probe env (via `_bridge_probe(extra_env=...)`).\n- [ ] With JIRA_API_TOKEN absent OR `--no-validate`, it SKIPS the probe, prints guidance, exits 0.\n- [ ] `JIRA_API_TOKEN` is env-only: guidance shown, NEVER written to any config file; uses `load_config().jira` (no new config layer).\n- [ ] `--url/--user/--project`, `--no-validate`, `--reset`, `--yes`, and `--help` (`src/rebar/_cli/help/jira-onboard.txt`) are supported; EOF/empty input aborts with no partial write.\n- [ ] `--reset` clears the three jira keys then exits (confirm unless `--yes`; decline -> exit 1).\n- [ ] Documented: `--help` text + a wizard section in `docs/jira-sync-setup.md` reconciled with existing manual steps; an ADR records the never-touch-pyproject + stdlib-only-write decisions.\n- [ ] Tests (`tests/unit/test_jira_onboard.py`): detect existing-vs-missing; persist to rebar.toml `[jira]` preserving other sections; create rebar.toml when only pyproject exists (pyproject byte-unchanged); existing rebar.toml in inline-table form `jira = {..}` and dotted-key form `jira.url=..` round-trips WITHOUT a duplicate section; token NEVER written; malformed rebar.toml caught (no write); `--reset` clears-and-exits; EOF/empty-input aborts (no write); JIRA_API_TOKEN-absent skips probe (exit 0); `_bridge_probe(extra_env=...)` overlays env. Full suite green.\n\n## Files\n- `src/rebar/_cli/_jira_onboard.py` (new; wizard + entry `_jira_onboard`)\n- `src/rebar/_cli/__init__.py` (intercept wiring + `_bridge_probe(extra_env=...)`)\n- `src/rebar/_cli/help/jira-onboard.txt` (new)\n- `src/rebar/config.py` (new `write_jira_config` + `_emit_toml`)\n- `docs/jira-sync-setup.md` (wizard section + reconcile manual steps)\n- `docs/adr/0001-jira-onboard-config-write.md` (new ADR: never-touch-pyproject, stdlib-only write)\n- `tests/unit/test_jira_onboard.py` (new)"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782782068323297001,"uuid":"20de6d2b-41aa-4350-82e2-afdff7ca10be"}